Brute force approach: 
1) Step 1: Understand what NOT to do

Your first instinct might be:

“Loop from 0 to 10ⁿ and check each number”

❌ That’s brute force

For n = 8 → up to 100 million numbers
Too slow and not expected in interviews

👉 So we must avoid generating numbers

2) Problem in brute force

For each number x, you need to check:
👉 “Are all digits unique?”

✅ Approach 1: Using Array (Best for understanding)
💡 Idea
Extract digits
Mark them in an array
If digit repeats → not unique

public int countNumbersWithUniqueDigits(int n) {
    int limit = (int)Math.pow(10, n);
    int count = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < limit; i++) {
        if (isUnique(i)) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    return count;
}

public boolean isUnique(int num) {
    int[] freq = new int[10]; // digits 0–9

    while (num > 0) {
        int digit = num % 10;

        if (freq[digit] == 1) {
            return false; // already seen
        }

        freq[digit] = 1;
        num = num / 10;
    }

    return true;
}
Complexity (for checking one number)
Time: O(d) → d = number of digits ≈ log n
Space:
Array → O(1)
Set → O(d)
Bitmask → O(1)

